// Fires when sessions-hub logs a collector.event with level=error within the
// last hour — i.e. machine-side collector errors that a collector reported
// and the hub relayed into its own structured logs.
//
// This does NOT catch sessions-telemetry-gateway's own upstream-forward
// failures (see the `collector.event`/level=error log line in
// hub/gateway/telemetry-gateway.ts), even though that line uses the same
// event name. Per the deploy runbook (infra/cf/telemetry.md), only
// sessions-hub has observability.logs/traces destinations configured — the
// gateway does not, and MUST NOT: the gateway IS the /v1/{logs,traces} sink,
// so exporting its own logs back to itself would be a recursion loop. That
// log line exists for local `wrangler tail`/dashboard visibility only; it
// never reaches OTelLogs. Gateway-side failures (Entra auth breaking, the
// DCR endpoint rejecting requests, etc.) instead manifest as an ABSENCE of
// data in Azure — including the hub's own hub.heartbeat events, which are
// relayed through the same gateway — so they're caught by
// missed-heartbeat.kql's watchdog-gauge alert and by the independent
// /healthz availability webtest (infra/azure/provision.sh), not by this query.
//
// See missed-heartbeat.kql for the OTelLogs/Body-as-JSON assumption this query
// shares. The hub relays each collector error as
// { event: "collector.event", machine: <id>, payload: { level, code, message, ... } }
// (hub/src/api/ops.ts). The machine-supplied fields are NESTED under `payload` on
// purpose: `event` and `machine` are hub-controlled (machine from the cert
// identity), so a collector cannot forge `event: "hub.certs.cf_auth_failed"` (or
// any hub event) to spoof an alert — its fields can only ever land inside
// `payload`. That is why this query reads level/code/message from body.payload.*,
// not body.*. ASSUMPTION TO VERIFY AT M4 DEPLOY: confirm the table/column names
// once real data flows, and confirm `level` (not `severity` or the OTLP-native
// SeverityText column) is the field the nested JSON payload uses.

// `otel` wraps OTelLogs in `union isfuzzy=true` so a missing table (before the
// first OTLP log lands) degrades to empty instead of erroring the whole rule —
// see missed-heartbeat.kql's "Missing-table guard" note for the full rationale.
let otel = union isfuzzy=true
    (datatable(TimeGenerated:datetime, Body:string)[]),
    (OTelLogs | project TimeGenerated, Body);
otel
| where TimeGenerated > ago(1h)
| extend body = todynamic(Body)
| where body.event == "collector.event" and body.payload.level == "error"
| extend machine = tostring(body.machine), code = tostring(body.payload.code), message = tostring(body.payload.message)
| project TimeGenerated, machine, level = tostring(body.payload.level), code, message
